If I have a function `bool ValidateString(string? input)`, then I can annotate it to indicate that if the return is `true` then `input` is not null:
```csharp
public static bool ValidateString([NotNullWhen(true)] string? input)
```
Is it possible to do that (or something similar) for a member of a parameter? `MemberNotNullWhen` looks a bit like what I'm after, but I don't think it can be applied to parameters. I'm thinking something along the lines of
```csharp
public class AClass { string? NullableString {get;set;}}
public static bool ValidateObject([ParameterMemberNotNullWhen(true, nameof(AClass.NullableString))] AClass input)
```
So then I could write
```csharp
public class AClass
{
    public string? NullableString { get; set; }
}

public static bool ValidateObject([ParameterMemberNotNullWhen(true, nameof(AClass.NullableString))] AClass input)
{
    return input.NullableString is not null;
}

static void Main(string[] _)
{
    var foo = new AClass();
    if (ValidateObject(foo))
    {
        Console.WriteLine(foo.NullableString.Length); // CS8602 Dereference of a possibly null reference.
    }
    Console.ReadLine();
}
```
without getting a warning about `foo.NullableString.Length`.

I don't know how feasible something like that would be, given that the member could change value on each read - but then again I don't imagine that's a particularly common scenario, and I guess you'd just not use such an annotation if that's how the member behaved.

